                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d264">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">715.1715/1364: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Assistant to the Special Representative of the
                        President</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ocheltree</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">San José</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-11-24T10:00:00-06:00"
                            >November 24, 1938—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 1:55 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>96. Referring to Dr. Corrigan’s telegram No. 95, November 6, 1 p.m., Dr.
                    Rodriguez has wired his personal acceptance of the proposal for an aerial survey
                    of the region of the Segovia River. The President of the Commission before
                    departing for Lima is sending notes to the Governments of Honduras and Nicaragua
                    proposing the survey and further extension of article No. III of the pact of
                    December 10, 1937.</p>
                <p>I am leaving for Panama today in accordance with the Department’s telegraphic
                    instruction No. 45, October 26, 7 p.m.<note n="59" xml:id="d264fn59">Not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Ocheltree</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
